A $1.75 trillion spending bill was making its way through Congress , where it passed in November 2021. However, a key Democratic Senator blocked the bill in the Senate claiming that it was objectionable as the bill contained a cornucopia of progressive entitlements, inflationary pressures and&nbsp;&nbsp;universal handouts.&nbsp;

As a result of the blockage by the Senator,&nbsp;&nbsp;some economists lowered expectations for U.S. economic growth next year, causing an already gloomy&nbsp;&nbsp;economic landscape spawned by the spread of the CoVID Omicron variant, to look even more tenebrous.&nbsp;&nbsp;

Goldman Sachs announced that it had lowered its growth forecast from 3 percent to 2 percent in the first quarter of 2022; 3.5 percent to 3 percent in the second and from 3 percent to 2.75 percent in the third, Bloomberg reported.

One key element that could slow economic&nbsp;growth is the reduction of the enhanced tax credit that enabled families to collect up to $300 per child but that is set to expire on December 31, 2021.&nbsp;

While the Federal&nbsp;&nbsp;Reserve announced in early December that it would double the pace of its bond buying wind down as a result of high employment growth&nbsp;&nbsp;and the surge in inflation,&nbsp;&nbsp;it could prove difficult for the U.S. Central bank&nbsp;&nbsp;to roll out its three proposed interest rate hikes if the economy grew at a slower pace than initially expected.&nbsp;

What does the Build Back Better Plan contain, and what would be its impact on the US economy if it passed? Here are the key elements of President&nbsp;&nbsp;Biden’s “BBB” plan:

I. The plan would implement two tax relief programs immediately; i)&nbsp;The expanded child tax credit and ii)&nbsp;The earned income tax credit. These tax reliefs translate to higher government spending compared to the revenues it takes in. By virtue of increased government spending,&nbsp;consumer demand will increase, spurring a modest increase in inflation.&nbsp;&nbsp;With inflation already being at near record highs,&nbsp;many economists are unanimous in their belief that higher inflationary pressures would increase the economic cost of bringing inflation back under control.&nbsp;

II.&nbsp;&nbsp;Universal Pre -K&nbsp;&nbsp;- The plan establishes universal and free Pre school for more than 6 million 3-4 year olds. Parents will be able to send their children to high quality pre-school in the setting&nbsp;of their choice -&nbsp;from public school to child care providers to Head&nbsp;Start.&nbsp;

III. Climate Investments - The plan sets aside $550 billion for clean energy and other climate change initiatives, including an enhancement of existing home energy and efficiency tax credits, an electrification focused rebate program and a&nbsp;&nbsp;credit of up to $12,500&nbsp;&nbsp;for union-made (U.S.) electrical vehicles.&nbsp;

IV. Extended Medicaid coverage&nbsp;&nbsp;and reduced premiums for Affordable Care Act coverage&nbsp;&nbsp;for which the plan sets aside $130 billion.&nbsp;&nbsp;It is estimated to drop premiums for an estimated 9 million people by an average of $600 per year.&nbsp;

V.&nbsp;&nbsp;The plan sets aside $150 billion for Affordable Housing to include down payment assistance for first generation home buyers, investment in rental assistance and housing vouchers and&nbsp;&nbsp;construction and rehabilitation of more than 1 million affordable homes across the United States.&nbsp;

All of the above measures involve a significant amount of Federal spending.&nbsp;&nbsp;To discern why perhaps this bill may not serve the best interest of the US economy, economists point to the following flagrancies:

&nbsp;a. This is the fourth multi trillion dollar spending bill that the House has passed in the past 12 months. First to pass was the $1 trillion CoVID relief bill passed in the waning days of the Trump presidency. Next&nbsp;in March this year, Congress passed a $1.9 trillion bill for certain states that shut down their economies the year before the pandemic. Then, in November of 2021, the House passed another $1.2 trillion&nbsp;bill that included subsidies for green energy programs. Critics call attention to the fact that spending $6-$7 trillion combined (from all the bills including this proposed “BBB” bill)), is not judicious when the economy is already in a recovery. To these critics, this type of spending in times of recovery is a harbinger of runaway inflation.&nbsp;

b. While proponents of the bill argue that the bill seeks to mitigate income inequalities, they do not acknowledge the loophole introduced in the bill that allows the wealthy to deduct state and local taxes from their federal tax bills, effectively allowing them to pay less federal income tax.

Being almost year end, it is highly unlikely that the bill will&nbsp;&nbsp;pass in the Senate. It may likely be resurrected early next year, albeit with amended clauses.&nbsp;&nbsp;If passed, the bill’s&nbsp;impact on the US economy will likely play out as a dénouement from a high adrenaline filled Hollywood action movie. To lend clarity to the statement, the unraveling of the effects of the bill’s passage on the economy will likely be tumultuous for a majority of consumers. The confluence of high inflation and rising demand for goods and services by virtue of increased government spending, may not be efficacious&nbsp;apropos to economic growth . At this juncture, we can only say&nbsp;&nbsp;“Spem Optimam!”
